Interview Explanation (Ready to Speak)

"The brute-force solution scans both the left and right side for every building, resulting in O(n²) time complexity. While analyzing it, I noticed that the right maximum is recomputed repeatedly for each index. To avoid this repeated computation, I precompute the right maximum in one traversal from right to left. During the second traversal, I maintain the left maximum using a single variable because it depends only on the elements already visited. At every index, the trapped water is calculated using min(leftMax, rightMax[i]) - height[i]. If the value is positive, I add it to the total. This reduces the overall time complexity to O(n) while using O(n) extra space."

Interview Follow-up Questions
Q1. Why do we take the minimum?

Because the water level is limited by the shorter boundary.

If one side is lower, water will overflow from that side.

Q2. Why is LeftMax maintained in a variable?

Since we are moving from left to right,

we already know the tallest building seen so far.

So one variable is sufficient.

Q3. Why is RightMax precomputed?

Right maximum depends on future elements.

Without precomputation,

we would scan the right side repeatedly,

leading to O(n²).

Q4. Can this be optimized further?

Yes.

Using the Two Pointer technique.

